Class AbstractBijection<A,B>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
      • io.github.utk003.util.data.collection.bijection.AbstractBijection<A,B>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - The type of objects in the first set of this bijection
    B - The type of objects in the second set of this bijection
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Bijection<A,B>, Iterable<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>, Collection<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MapBackedBijection

    public abstract class AbstractBijection<A,B>
extends AbstractCollection<Bijection.Pairing<A,B>>
implements Bijection<A,B>
    A skeletal implementation of the Bijection interface, provided to minimize the effort required to implement the interface.

    Any classes that extend AbstractBijection must implement the Collection.size(), Collection.iterator(), Bijection.containsPairing(Pairing), Bijection.addPairing(Pairing), and Bijection.removePairing(Pairing) methods. Additionally, other methods may (and probably should) be re-implemented if the underlying nature of the subclass makes a more efficient implementation possible.

        public boolean containsPairing(@NotNull
                               A obj1,
                               @NotNull
                               B obj2)
        Returns whether or not this Bijection contains the specified mapping.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        containsPairing(new Pairing<>(obj1, obj2))}
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.

      • toPairedArray

        @NotNull
public @NotNull Object[][] toPairedArray(boolean makeRowsPairwise)
        Returns this bijection as a 2D array.

        If the argument makeRowsPairwise is true, then the returned 2D array will have dimensions Nx2, where N is the number of mappings in this bijection. Each of the N rows of the array will correspond to a unique mapping of this Bijection.

        If the argument makeRowsPairwise is false, then the returned 2D array will have dimensions 2xN, where N is the number of mappings in this bijection. This will essentially be an array of the two arrays returned by Bijection.toPairedArray().

        Specified by:
        toPairedArray in interface Bijection<A,B>
        Parameters:
        makeRowsPairwise - Whether to return an Nx2 or 2xN array
        Returns:
        This Bijection as a 2D array
        See Also:
        Bijection.toPairedArray()

      • addPairing

        public abstract boolean addPairing(@NotNull
                                   @NotNull Bijection.Pairing<A,B> pairing)
        Adds the specified Pairing to this Bijection, if possible.

        This method is equivalent to running 

        addPairing(pairing.getFirst(), pairing.getSecond())
        As a result, only one of these two methods should be explicitly defined. If both are overridden, then both implementations must have exactly the same effect on the internal state of this Bijection.

        This method returns false regardless of whether the method failed due to the defined pairing existing or due to conflicts with other existing pairings. For a method that throws an exception if the new pairing conflicts, use Bijection.addPairingOrFail(Pairing), or alternatively use Bijection.containsPairing(Pairing) to see if the addition failed due to the pairing already existing.

        Specified by:
        addPairing in interface Bijection<A,B>
        Parameters:
        pairing - The pairing to add
        Returns:
        Whether or not this Bijection was modified by this method
        See Also:
        Bijection.addPairing(Object, Object), Bijection.addPairingOrFail(Pairing)

      • addPairingOrFail

        public boolean addPairingOrFail(@NotNull
                                @NotNull Bijection.Pairing<A,B> pairing)
        Adds the specified Pairing to this Bijection, if possible.

        This method completes successfully if and only if the pairing does not conflict with any already existing pairings in the bijection. If this is the case, then this method is identical to Bijection.addPairing(Pairing). However, if this new pairing does conflict with a pre-existing pairing, then this method throws an IllegalStateException instead.

        Specified by:
        addPairingOrFail in interface Bijection<A,B>
        Parameters:
        pairing - The pairing to add
        Returns:
        Whether or not this Bijection was modified by this method
        See Also:
        Bijection.addPairing(Pairing)
